Verenigd Koninkrijk","Rivenhall, Essex, England":"Rivenhall, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1356–":"1356–Deceased","1356–1446":"1356–1446","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","1358–Female":"1358–Deceased","1361–1446":"1361–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Deceased","1358–1380":"1358–1380","–Female":"Deceased","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1335–1378":"1335–1378","1340–1383":"1340–1383","4 Sep 1693":"4 September 1693","1484":"1484","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1358":"1358","1446":"1446","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1355":"1355","1366":"1366","1405":"1405","Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Rivenhall, Essex, England":"Rivenhall, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Smythe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Smith  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Smith","meanings":["English and Scottish: occupational name denoting a worker in metal, especially iron, such as a blacksmith or farrier, from Middle English <i>smith</i> ‘smith’ (Old English <i>smith</i>, probably a derivative of <i>smītan</i> ‘to strike, hammer’). Early examples are also found in the Latin form   Faber  . Metal-working was one of the earliest occupations for which specialist skills were required, and its importance ensured that this term and its equivalents in other languages were the most widespread of all occupational surnames in Europe. Medieval smiths were important not only in making horseshoes, plowshares, and other domestic articles, but above all for their skill in forging swords, other weapons, and armor. This is also the most frequent of all surnames in the US. It is very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below). This surname (in any of the two possible English senses; see also below) is also found in Haiti. See also   Smither  .","English: from Middle English <i>smithe</i> ‘smithy, forge’ (Old English <i>smiththe</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a blacksmith's shop, occupational, for someone who worked in one, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Smitha in King's Nympton (Devon). Compare   Smithey  .","Irish and Scottish: sometimes adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Gobhann</b>, Irish <b>Mac Gabhann</b> ‘son of the smith’. See   McGowan  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":26,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":99,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Gilbert Smythe was born in 1356, in Essex, England, his father, Sir Thomas Smythe of Carrington, was 21 and his mother, Lady Margaret de Ros, was 16. He married Anne Geron Gordon in 1380, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Rivenhall, Essex, England."},"et":{"1356–":"1356–Surnud","1356–1446":"1356–1446","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1358–Female":"1358–Surnud","1361–1446":"1361–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1358–1380":"1358–1380","–Female":"Surnud","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1335–1378":"1335–1378","1340–1383":"1340–1383","4 Sep 1693":"4. september 1693","1484":"1484","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1358":"1358","1446":"1446","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1378":"1378","1355":"1355","1366":"1366","1405":"1405","Rivenhall, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Rivenhall, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Rivenhall, Essex, England":"Rivenhall, Essex, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1356–":"1356–Kuollut","1356–1446":"1356–1446","1356–Male":"1356–Kuollut","1358–Female":"1358–Kuollut","1361–1446":"1361–1446","1366–Female":"1366–Kuollut","1358–1380":"1358–1380","–Female":"Kuollut","1405–1484":"1405–1484","1335–1378":"1335–1378","1340–1383":"1340–1383","4 Sep 1693":"4. syyskuuta 1693","1484":"1484","1340":"1340","1383":"1383","1361":"1361","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1358":"1358","1446":"1446","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1455":"1455","1378":"1378